                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.51A/519: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Matthews</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-18T23:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 18, 1942—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 18—7:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1298. I duly informed Sir Alexander Cadogan in the sense of the Department’s
                    instruction No. 1034, March 11, midnight. He tells me that he is awaiting a
                    report which was requested from Sir Reader Bullard<note n="3" xml:id="d246fn3"
                        >British Minister in Iran.</note> following my earlier conversation with
                    him, (my telegram No. 1050, March 5, 7 p.m.). He assures me, however, that the
                    Foreign Office “unreservedly welcome the principle of Anglo-United States
                    cooperation in Persian questions” and fully share the view that such cooperation
                    is the best means of strengthening the position in Persia to the advantage of
                    the cause of the Allies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Matthews</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
